\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {2}{\ignorespaces \textbf  {Choosing the sampler and the likelihood-score approximation from problem geometry.} The diffusion $g_\tau $ selects the sampler (deterministic ODE vs.\ calibrated SDE); the observation regime selects the covariance (cheap Jacobian-free for dense/informative observations, where all samplers nearly coincide, vs.\ the inflated covariance for sparse observations, where it is markedly more accurate); and high dimensionality selects the ensemble-shared evaluation of the source covariance, which removes the per-member cost. The number of steps $M$ and ensemble size $E$ trade accuracy and calibration against cost.\relax }}{11}{figure.caption.9}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:decision_guide}{{2}{11}{\textbf {Choosing the sampler and the likelihood-score approximation from problem geometry.} The diffusion $\gdiff _\tau $ selects the sampler (deterministic ODE vs.\ calibrated SDE); the observation regime selects the covariance (cheap Jacobian-free for dense/informative observations, where all samplers nearly coincide, vs.\ the inflated covariance for sparse observations, where it is markedly more accurate); and high dimensionality selects the ensemble-shared evaluation of the source covariance, which removes the per-member cost. The number of steps $M$ and ensemble size $E$ trade accuracy and calibration against cost.\relax }{figure.caption.9}{}}
